    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-06-18T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-06-18T14:00:00-05:00" n="668"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d668">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.00/880: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Honduras</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HL1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Higgins</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-06-18T13:00:00-06:00"
                            >June 18, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:33 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>54. Department’s circular telegram of June 17, 6 p.m. Slight reaction here to
                        <persName corresp="#p_MH1">Martínez</persName> manifesto because the general
                    belief previously existed that he never had any intention to resign. On June
                    10th press published inconspicuously text of manifesto without comment then or
                    subsequently. The Minister of Foreign Affairs however on that date remarked to
                    me on his own initiative that inasmuch as <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Martínez</persName> had been permitted to seize all the customs revenues he
                    might <pb facs="0709" n="605" xml:id="pg_605"/> maintain himself in power
                    indefinitely. Those in government circles regret <persName corresp="#p_MH1"
                        >Martínez</persName>’s staying on but the anti-Americans of which there are
                    many in Honduras are elated over his determination and success in remaining in
                    spite of our nonrecognition. Both his determination and success are of course
                    encouraging to the elements here contemplating or desiring revolution.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Higgins</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
